name: 2-hydroxy-5-nitronicotinic acid

Benzene has a melting point of 5.5 degrees Celsius. The effects of the functional groups are as follows: Nitro group (+NO2) significantly increases the melting point due to its ability to participate in intermolecular hydrogen bonding and its electron-withdrawing nature, which stabilizes the ionic form in the solid state (+80 to +100). Hydroxy group (-OH) also increases melting point due to hydrogen bonding (+40 to +50). Carboxylic acid group (-COOH) has a very high impact on melting point due to its ability to form strong dimeric hydrogen bonds (+70 to +80). The pyridine ring (cyclic compound with one nitrogen atom) generally has a higher melting point than benzene due to its increased polarity and potential for hydrogen bond formation, but since it is being compared to benzene here, we will consider it as part of the base structure. Lastly, the effect of the additional carbon-oxygen double bond (C=O) within the carboxylic group is included in its overall contribution as it is not a separate substituent but part of the carboxylic acid functionality. Therefore, the overall change in melting point would be the sum of the contributions of the nitro, hydroxy, and carboxylic acid groups relative to benzene.
Prediction: 235.5 to 275.5 (this range includes the sum of benzene's 5.5 + nitro group's 80 to 100 + hydroxy group's 40 to 50 + carboxylic acid's 70 to 80)
